<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0114</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Federation for Industry Sector Skills and Standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Federation for Industry Sector Skills and Standards is responsible for the certification of every Apprentice in England, Scotland and Wales (unfunded as well as funded). Since it took on this responsibility (January 2012) it has certified over 360,000 Apprentices, reduced the cost by 25% (£2.7m), improved quality and consistency, and reduced bureaucracy through intelligent regulation. We also work with and for the 18 Sector Skills Councils who engage with 550,000 employers. They develop the current Apprenticeship Frameworks in addition to a significant number of other actions in the skills development world.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">We strongly support the objectives of the Richard Review and the Government’s desire to engage more deeply and widely with more Employers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our starting point is that deregulation that reduces cost and bureaucratic burdens on Employers is positive, set within the context of intelligent regulation. We wish to see that happen for Employer engagement with Apprenticeships.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our major concern in the Draft De-Regulation Bill is that in relation to Apprenticeships there will be a reduction in Act of Parliament defined regulation (ASCL 2010), but we are unsure about what (if any) regulation on businesses might replace it as that is yet to be set out by the Secretary of State. The underpinning principle is that it needs to be simpler and quicker to help businesses take part.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Currently the complex and bureaucratic system is managed by training providers (3,500) on behalf of Employers. We want to ensure that this is simplified with a significantly simpler set of subsidies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">andegulations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which encourage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">businesses particularly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">micos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and SMEs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to take on Apprentices by owning the system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We support the principle of the reforms, but at present have more questions than answers or views which we believe the Coalition Government needs to address before pressing ahead.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We have three points we agree with in the De-Regulation Bill in relation to Apprenticeships. These are:</span></a></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Abolition of the Chief Executive of Skills Funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – this we believe is a purely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">administrative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> process resulting from the Skills Funding Agency being subsumed within BIS.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Removal of SASE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – while some guidance as to what is and is not acceptable is necessary, SASE is at the same time too rigid and too vague. It applies to every Apprenticeship framework and given that each industry and each Framework is different causes a lot of problems. Its removal and probable replacement with a requirement for a certain level of English and Maths in every Apprenticeship Standard and the flexibility of each new Apprenticeship Standard to be defined by Employers is to be welcomed (if that is what is introduced).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Transition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We are encouraged by the implication in the Draft Bill that the new regulations will be implemented over a period and not in one go as this will give Apprentices/Employers/Training Providers and Government as well as the system as a whole the capacity to adjust to a radical change.</span><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></li></ul><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We have a number of questions about the regulatory framework that is not yet announced and these are:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The current funding structure is very complex and needs radical simplification if Employers are to engage directly. We would like to see radical simplification. Will the funding structure be simplified so a micro business can understand it?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If businesses are to engage minimal bureaucracy should be imposed on them. What is the estimated cost in time and money for a micro business and SME of the new regulations compared to the existing ones?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How will the Secretary of State measure what an adequate Apprenticeship Standard looks like?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Will the new regulations ensure that the current very low level of fraudulent use of public money continues?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We have a number of suggestions/points and these are:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The new system has regulatory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that can flex between the different needs of each industry/occupation, rather than being a rigid set of rules.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support the nascent industrial partnerships which are funded as part of UKCES EOS2 pilots as they are Employer owned and we urge the Government to ensure that within this Bill and the new regulations nothing is introduced that restricts them.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">believe that the changes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the Apprenticeship system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be implemented </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by fully piloting them in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">industrial partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (funded under EOS2 – Trailblazers) and learning lessons before rolling out a framework that enables each industry to set its own working arrangements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A self-regulated quality assurance system managed by the industrial partnerships and/or the Federation for:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the development of new Apprenticeship Standards with wide buy in and ownership from each industry/occupation they apply to</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a testing regime that measures the knowledge and competence of the Apprentice at the point of becoming an Apprentice (and if required on the way through)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensuring the transparency of the services offered and managing potential conflicts of interest</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">spreading best practice</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensuring consistency in standards of delivery</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.11pt; padding-left:6.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">monitoring the intelligent regulatory system</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Federation has work underway for a self-regulatory system.</span></li></ol></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndustrial partnerships </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should to engage with and have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">demonstrable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wide employer support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Apprenticeship Standard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">developed under the ownership of the industrial partnership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that define what the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">majority of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Employers in that industry want the Apprentice to be able to do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> when they qualify (see quality assurance system above)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An assessment system dictated by the needs of the Apprenticeship Standard and developed by the industrial partnership. This does not necessarily mean just an end test (like a Driving Exam, which has theory and practice), but could be a combination of theoretical and competence based testing, either or both during and at the end(see quality assurance system above)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An intelligent regulatory framework that minimises bureaucracy while safeguarding the expenditure of public money.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(see quality assurance system above)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The industrial partnership could become a purchasing consortium, on behalf of the Employers in the industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (particularly micros and SMEs)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and negotiate with one or more training providers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to enhance their buying power</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>